[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [1msudo [22mallows a permitted user to execute a [4mcommand[24m as the superuser or
       another user, as specified in the [4msudoers[24m file.  The real and effective
       uid and gid are set to match those of the target user as specified in
       the passwd file and the group vector is initialized based on the group
       file (unless the [1m-P [22moption was specified).  If the invoking user is
       root or if the target user is the same as the invoking user, no
       password is required.  Otherwise, [1msudo [22mrequires that users authenticate
       themselves with a password by default (NOTE: in the default
       configuration this is the user's password, not the root password).
       Once a user has been authenticated, a time stamp is updated and the
       user may then use sudo without a password for a short period of time (5
       minutes unless overridden in [4msudoers[24m).

       When invoked as [1msudoedit[22m, the [1m-e [22moption (described below), is implied.

       [1msudo [22mdetermines who is an authorized user by consulting the file
       [4m/etc/sudoers[24m.  By running [1msudo [22mwith the [1m-v [22moption, a user can update
       the time stamp without running a [4mcommand[24m.  If a password is required,
       [1msudo [22mwill exit if the user's password is not entered within a
       configurable time limit.  The default password prompt timeout is 5
       minutes.

       If a user who is not listed in the [4msudoers[24m file tries to run a command
       via [1msudo[22m, mail is sent to the proper authorities, as defined at
       configure time or in the [4msudoers[24m file (defaults to root).  Note that
       the mail will not be sent if an unauthorized user tries to run sudo
       with the [1m-l [22mor [1m-v [22moption.  This allows users to determine for
       themselves whether or not they are allowed to use [1msudo[22m.

       If [1msudo [22mis run by root and the SUDO_USER environment variable is set,
       [1msudo [22mwill use this value to determine who the actual user is.  This can
       be used by a user to log commands through sudo even when a root shell
       has been invoked.  It also allows the [1m-e [22moption to remain useful even
       when being run via a sudo-run script or program.  Note however, that
       the sudoers lookup is still done for root, not the user specified by
       SUDO_USER.

       [1msudo [22mcan log both successful and unsuccessful attempts (as well as
       errors) to [4msyslog[24m(3), a log file, or both.  By default [1msudo [22mwill log
       via [4msyslog[24m(3) but this is changeable at configure time or via the
       [4msudoers[24m file.

