[1mRETURN VALUES[0m
       Upon successful execution of a program, the exit status from [1msudo [22mwill
       simply be the exit status of the program that was executed.

       Otherwise, [1msudo [22mquits with an exit value of 1 if there is a
       configuration/permission problem or if [1msudo [22mcannot execute the given
       command.  In the latter case the error string is printed to stderr.  If
       [1msudo [22mcannot [4mstat[24m(2) one or more entries in the user's PATH an error is
       printed on stderr.  (If the directory does not exist or if it is not
       really a directory, the entry is ignored and no error is printed.)
       This should not happen under normal circumstances.  The most common
       reason for [4mstat[24m(2) to return "permission denied" is if you are running
       an automounter and one of the directories in your PATH is on a machine
       that is currently unreachable.

[1mSECURITY NOTES[0m
       [1msudo [22mtries to be safe when executing external commands.

       There are two distinct ways to deal with environment variables.  By
       default, the [4menv_reset[24m [4msudoers[24m option is enabled.  This causes commands
       to be executed with a minimal environment containing TERM, PATH, HOME,
       SHELL, LOGNAME, USER and USERNAME in addition to variables from the
       invoking process permitted by the [4menv_check[24m and [4menv_keep[24m [4msudoers[0m
       options.  There is effectively a whitelist for environment variables.

       If, however, the [4menv_reset[24m option is disabled in [4msudoers[24m, any variables
       not explicitly denied by the [4menv_check[24m and [4menv_delete[24m options are
       inherited from the invoking process.  In this case, [4menv_check[24m and
       [4menv_delete[24m behave like a blacklist.  Since it is not possible to
       blacklist all potentially dangerous environment variables, use of the
       default [4menv_reset[24m behavior is encouraged.

       In all cases, environment variables with a value beginning with () are
       removed as they could be interpreted as [1mbash [22mfunctions.  The list of
       environment variables that [1msudo [22mallows or denies is contained in the
       output of sudo -V when run as root.

       Note that the dynamic linker on most operating systems will remove
       variables that can control dynamic linking from the environment of
       setuid executables, including [1msudo[22m.  Depending on the operating system
       this may include _RLD*, DYLD_*, LD_*, LDR_*, LIBPATH, SHLIB_PATH, and
       others.  These type of variables are removed from the environment
       before [1msudo [22meven begins execution and, as such, it is not possible for
       [1msudo [22mto preserve them.

       To prevent command spoofing, [1msudo [22mchecks "." and "" (both denoting
       current directory) last when searching for a command in the user's PATH
       (if one or both are in the PATH).  Note, however, that the actual PATH
       environment variable is [4mnot[24m modified and is passed unchanged to the
       program that [1msudo [22mexecutes.

       [1msudo [22mwill check the ownership of its time stamp directory
       ([4m/var/adm/sudo[24m by default) and ignore the directory's contents if it is
       not owned by root or if it is writable by a user other than root.  On
       systems that allow non-root users to give away files via [4mchown[24m(2), if
       the time stamp directory is located in a directory writable by anyone
       (e.g., [4m/tmp[24m), it is possible for a user to create the time stamp
       directory before [1msudo [22mis run.  However, because [1msudo [22mchecks the
       ownership and mode of the directory and its contents, the only damage
       that can be done is to "hide" files by putting them in the time stamp
       dir.  This is unlikely to happen since once the time stamp dir is owned
       by root and inaccessible by any other user, the user placing files
       there would be unable to get them back out.  To get around this issue
       you can use a directory that is not world-writable for the time stamps
       ([4m/var/adm/sudo[24m for instance) or create [4m/var/adm/sudo[24m with the
       appropriate owner (root) and permissions (0700) in the system startup
       files.

       [1msudo [22mwill not honor time stamps set far in the future.  Timestamps with
       a date greater than current_time + 2 * TIMEOUT will be ignored and sudo
       will log and complain.  This is done to keep a user from creating
       his/her own time stamp with a bogus date on systems that allow users to
       give away files.

       On systems where the boot time is available, [1msudo [22mwill also not honor
       time stamps from before the machine booted.

       Since time stamp files live in the file system, they can outlive a
       user's login session.  As a result, a user may be able to login, run a
       command with [1msudo [22mafter authenticating, logout, login again, and run
       [1msudo [22mwithout authenticating so long as the time stamp file's
       modification time is within 5 minutes (or whatever the timeout is set
       to in [4msudoers[24m).  When the [4mtty_tickets[24m option is enabled in [4msudoers[24m, the
       time stamp has per-tty granularity but still may outlive the user's
       session.  On Linux systems where the devpts filesystem is used, Solaris
       systems with the devices filesystem, as well as other systems that
       utilize a devfs filesystem that monotonically increase the inode number
       of devices as they are created (such as Mac OS X), [1msudo [22mis able to
       determine when a tty-based time stamp file is stale and will ignore it.
       Administrators should not rely on this feature as it is not universally
       available.

       Please note that [1msudo [22mwill normally only log the command it explicitly
       runs.  If a user runs a command such as sudo su or sudo sh, subsequent
       commands run from that shell will [4mnot[24m be logged, nor will [1msudo[22m's access
       control affect them.  The same is true for commands that offer shell
       escapes (including most editors).  Because of this, care must be taken
       when giving users access to commands via [1msudo [22mto verify that the
       command does not inadvertently give the user an effective root shell.
       For more information, please see the PREVENTING SHELL ESCAPES section
       in [4msudoers[24m(4).

