[1mCAVEATS[0m
       There is no easy way to prevent a user from gaining a root shell if
       that user is allowed to run arbitrary commands via [1msudo[22m.  Also, many
       programs (such as editors) allow the user to run commands via shell
       escapes, thus avoiding [1msudo[22m's checks.  However, on most systems it is
       possible to prevent shell escapes with [1msudo[22m's [4mnoexec[24m functionality.
       See the [4msudoers[24m(4) manual for details.

       It is not meaningful to run the cd command directly via sudo, e.g.,

        $ sudo cd /usr/local/protected

       since when the command exits the parent process (your shell) will still
       be the same.  Please see the EXAMPLES section for more information.

       If users have sudo ALL there is nothing to prevent them from creating
       their own program that gives them a root shell regardless of any '!'
       elements in the user specification.

       Running shell scripts via [1msudo [22mcan expose the same kernel bugs that
       make setuid shell scripts unsafe on some operating systems (if your OS
       has a /dev/fd/ directory, setuid shell scripts are generally safe).

